\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n1 Consent letters from petitioners and respondent to the filing of this brief concurrently are being forwarded to the Clerk of this Court.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The organizations which join in this brief are interested in insuring that minority children are afforded equal educational opportunity. They are as one in the belief that this cannot be done under a system of segregated schools. They do not believe that separate can be equal.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The particular purpose of each organization is set out in the Appendix.
\par \pard 
\par \b \i0 \ul0 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 TITLE: \b0 \i0 \ul0 BRIEF AMICI CURIAE IN SUPPORT OF PETITIONERS OF AFRICAN AMERICAN EDUCATION COMMISSION, COMMUNITY RELATIONS CONFERENCE OF SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA, MEXICAN-AMERICAN LEGAL DEFENSE AND EDUCATIONAL FUND, (Other Amici Curiae are set forth on inside cover)
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 SUMMARY OF ARGUMENT
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In this brief, we make two arguments: the first points to the lower court's failure to properly interpret Columbus Board of Education v. Penick, 443 U.S. 449 (1979) and Dayton Board of Education v. Brinkman, 443 U.S. 526 (1979) (Dayton II) and its consequent failure to identify Los Angeles segregation as de jure in character; alternatively, the second emphasizes the lower court's disregard of Village of Arlington Heights v. Metropolitan Housing Development Corp., 429 U.S. 252 (1977) in assessing Proposition 1's segregative purposes.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 First, we show that the court below misinterpreted Columbus and Dayton II. While it rightly understood that a school board can ordinarily \b \i0 \ul0 [*5]\b0 \i0 \ul0   pursue a neighborhood school policy without violating the federal constitution, it failed to appreciate that when a school board has a duty to desegregate it cannot act under color of law in systematic disregard of that duty without violating the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Amendments. In Dayton II, the duty was federally imposed; here the duty is state imposed. Whatever the source of the duty or the source of rights of minority children, a school board that systematically denies minority children their rights violates the federal constitution. The Constitution may itself impose no obligation for a state to disperse benefits or rights, but when it does, "the manner in which they disperse benefits is subject to constitutional limitations." Maher v. Roe, 434 U.S. 464, 470 (1977). The school board here has respected the rights of white children, but not of minority children. This it cannot do.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Second, since the trial court found there was no difference in remedy required for Los Angeles desegregation under California law or under federal decisional law it held no Arlington Heights evidentiary hearing.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The court below likewise held no evidentiary hearing and upheld the validity \b \i0 \ul0 [*6]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of Proposition 1 without regard to the evidence petitioners had presented to the trial court. That evidence overwhelmingly sustains petitioners' contention that Proposition 1 was and is racially motivated and, therefore, must, under Arlington Heights, be declared unconstitutional. Respondent presented no evidence to controvert petitioners' showing.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 We describe the impact of the official action, the historical background of the decision together with the specific sequence of events, and the departure from the normal procedural and substantive institutional policies which took place to demonstrate that the requirements of Arlington Heights have been met.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Finally, we argue that if the Court does not consider Arlington Heights to have been met, then it should remand the case to the trial court for the hearing.
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 ARGUMENT
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 I
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 THE LOWER COURT MISINTERPRETED COLUMBUS AND DAYTON II, FAILING TO APPRECIATE THAT THE SCHOOL BOARD'S BAD FAITH FAILURE TO RESPECT THE RIGHTS OF MINORITY CHILDREN UNDER STATE LAW ITSELF VIOLATED THE FEDERAL CONSTITUTION.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Los Angeles School Board, for many years, n2 has violated its state imposed duty to desegregate its minority segregated schools and \b \i0 \ul0 [*7]\b0 \i0 \ul0   to confer the benefits owed under state law to minority children. The lower court has sadly misread Dayton II as well as those cases which recognize that state officials cannot respect the rights of white children while ignoring the rights of minority children. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n2 In this section, we concentrate as did the court below on the findings of the 1970 trial court as affirmed by the California Supreme Court in 1976.  Crawford v. Board of Education, 17 Cal.3d 280, 551 P.2d 28 (1976). Much of the material in the Arlington Heights section infra is relevant to this period and also shows the continuing recalcitrance of the Board. The Arlington Heights section presents background to show the purposes underlying Proposition 1. Here we show that segregation in Los Angeles is de jure, not de facto.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 A. The Existence Since 1963 of a State-Imposed Duty on the Los Angeles School Board to Desegregate
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In Crawford v. Board of Education, 17 Cal.3d 280, 551 P.2d 28 (1976) (Crawford I) the court traced the duty of school boards to desegregate back to Jackson v. Pasadena City School District, 59 Cal.2d 876, 382 P.2d 878 (1963). In Jackson, the court had declared \b \i0 \ul0 [*8]\b0 \i0 \ul0   that "the segregation of school children into separate schools because of their race, even though the physical facilities and the methods and quality of instruction in the several schools may be equal, deprives the children of the minority group of equal opportunities for education and denies them equal protection and due process of the law." 59 Cal.2d at 880.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In Crawford I the court observed that: "[S]ince Jackson, this court has consistently reiterated the principle that the constitutional obligations of school boards in California include an obligation to undertake reasonably feasible steps to alleviate school desegregation, regardless of its cause." 17 Cal.3d at 292. That state law duty was also recognized by the court of appeal below.  113 Cal.App.3d 633, 647, 170 Cal.Rptr. 495, 504 (1980) (hereinafter the court below or Crawford II). Accordingly, the state duty to desegregate has bound respondent board since 1963. Next we point to the judicial findings that the board has in bad faith persistently breached that duty.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 B. The Findings of the Lower Courts that the Board Has Continually Violated that Duty in Bad Faith
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The courts in Crawford \b \i0 \ul0 [*9]\b0 \i0 \ul0   I and Crawford II both recognized that the board had violated its obligations to minority children under state law. For example, in Crawford I, the court affirmed findings that the Board "'Has... since at least 1963, knowingly affirmatively and in bad faith" engaged in affirmative policies that segregated its students.  17 Cal. 3d at 288 (emphasis added). Specifically, the court found that the board had employed policies regarding (1) the siting and construction of new schools in a way leading to "heavy segregation"; (2) an open transfer policy with the "knowledge that such a policy would exacerbate school segregation because it would permit the more affluent white students to transfer out of minority segregated schools but at the same time could not be utilized by less affluent minority students to transfer into predominantly white schools"; (3) the use of feeder school policies that it "knew or should have known would create and perpetuate segregation in such higher grade schools"; and (4) the use of mandatory attendance areas and boundaries "so as to create or perpetuate segregated schools." See generally 17 Cal. 3d at 288-89.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Most revealing of all, Crawford \b \i0 \ul0 [*10]\b0 \i0 \ul0   I affirmed findings that the Board had given minority schools "teachers, physical facilities and curriculum... of poorer quality... than at its predominantly white schools.'" Id. at 289.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The findings are now not open to question; indeed the court in Crawford II repeats them.  113 Cal.App.3d at 642-43. The question is whether the lower court properly understood Columbus and Dayton II.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 C. The Bad Faith Failure of the Board to Respect Its Duty to Minority Children Violates Federal Law.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Court below failed to take the duty to desegregate and its bad faith violation into account in concluding that no de jure segregation was present. It cited Columbus and Dayton II for propositions that are not here relevant. For example, it cited Columbus for the idea that "[D]isparate impact and foreseeable consequences, without more, do not establish a constitutional violation." 113 Cal.Rptr. 3d at 641, quoting 443 U.S. at 464. It paraded Dayton II for the proposition that "We have never held that as a general proposition the foreseeability of segregative consequences makes out a prima facie case of purposeful racial discrimination." Id. at \b \i0 \ul0 [*11]\b0 \i0 \ul0   641, quoting Dayton II, 443 U.S. at 536 n.9. It proceeded to see no specific segregative intent (id. at 646) and, therefore, found no de jure segregation.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 What Crawford II ignored is that there is "something more" ( Columbus, 443 U.S. at 646) in this case: the bad faith violation of a duty to desegregate. Clearly where a federal duty to desegregate is involved, questions of specific intent go by the boards. As the court said in Dayton II, the measure of a school board's conduct under an "unsatisfied duty to liquidate a dual system is the effectiveness, not the purpose, of the actions in decreasing or increasing the segregation caused by the dual system." 443 U.S. at 53 (emphasis added). As the Court explained in Columbus, each instance of a failure or a refusal to fulfill this affirmative duty violates the Fourteenth Amendment. 443 U.S. at 667.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 We are at a loss to understand why the source of the duty makes the slightest difference. Our contention is not that the states had to create this duty; our contention rather is that once a duty to give to minority children the benefit of desegregated education has been established "the \b \i0 \ul0 [*12]\b0 \i0 \ul0   manner in which it dispenses benefits is subject to constitutional limitations." Maher v. Roe, 432 U.S. at 470. Indeed as the Court noted in Maher, (id.) the basic framework for analyzing claims such as these was set out in San Antonio School District v. Rodriguez, 411 U.S. 1, 17 (1973), "We must decide, first whether [the state action] operates to the disadvantage of some suspect class...."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Here that conclusion is obvious. The Board, as the findings below show, has affirmatively disregarded its obligation to minority children. It has served white children appreciating their needs, and respecting their rights while flagrantly ignoring the rights of minority children. This Court, even pre-Brown was ready to strike down state actions that favored white students over black. See, e.g.  Sweatt v. Painter, 339 U.S. 629 (1950); McLaurin v. Oklahoma State Regents, 339 U.S. 637 (1950) (no duty to have schools, but can not ignore needs of black students).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 What the Board has done is worse than providing separate but equal facilities. Here it has openly flouted the law. Acting under color of state law, it has persistently violated and ignored \b \i0 \ul0 [*13]\b0 \i0 \ul0   its duties under state law to minority children while serving white children. It should not be permitted to do this. "Equal protection of the laws is not achieved through indiscriminate imposition of equalities." Shelley v. Kramer, 334 U.S. 1, 22 (1948).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 II
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 PROPOSITION ONE IS UNCONSTITUTIONAL UNDER ARLINGTON HEIGHTS
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 A. Proposition One Has a Discriminatory Effect Because It Impedes Desegregation and Disadvantages Minorities
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 One of the relevant inquiries under Arlington Heights is whether the action has a discriminatory effect.  429 U.S. at 266.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 1. The Mandatory Plan
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Plans which included mandatory pupil assignment and transportation were in effect in the Los Angeles school system for the school years 1978-79, 1979-80, and most of 1980-81. With regard to the 1980 plan, a review of the enrollment statistics indicates (1) that the plan made substantial strides towards desegregating the participating minority schools and (2) since its withdrawal those schools have once again become segregated.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In 1980-81, forty-four minority elementary schools took part in the mandatory portion of the desegregation plan. In 41 of these schools there was an improvement \b \i0 \ul0 [*14]\b0 \i0 \ul0   in the minority-white ratio of students. The statistics indicate that the mandatory plan was successful in achieving desegregation of the participating minority schools. The real story, however, is reflected in the plight of these schools since the dismantling of the mandatory plan. Of the forty-four schools participating in the plan on the elementary school level, virtually every one has reverted to its previous segregated status.
