\row \pard \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*17]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Source: 1978, 1979, 1980 Racial and Ethnic Surveys; Preliminary Racial Ethnic Survey, Oct. 1981
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The PWT program was also found to be ineffective in achieving desegregation for the following reasons:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "There are usually only disadvantages to the sending school and few advantages. The minority sending school remains segregated. There is no history of a reverse PWT influx into sending schools by white students...."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "The minority child's PWT experience does not remove the stigma attached to the sending school or the stigma to the child of going from that sending school who understands that the school he would normally be assigned to would be an all-monority school were it not for his own effort to leave that school."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "[I]t is often the case that the PWT minority child is accorded a second class status in the receiving school in that he is continually subject to the threat of having his attendance at that school discontinued for disciplinary reasons when that sanction would not be applied to the resident student...."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 July 7 Opinion, pg. 20, 59 CT 17467-17468.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "That the history in this district of voluntary compliance with the mandate is one of failure in desegregating \b \i0 \ul0 [*18]\b0 \i0 \ul0   minority schools."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Finding of Fact No. 31, July 7, 1980 Opinion, p. 92, 59 CT. 17538
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This critical failing of PWT, i.e. the fact that it places a disproportionate burden on minority child children, is relevant in an analysis under
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Arlington Heights.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In determining whether official action has a discriminatory impact, consideration is given to whether the action "bears more heavily on one race than another." Arlington Heights, 429 U.S. at 266. This is certainly the case here. Time and again lower federal courts have rejected voluntary plans wherein the minority students bear the full burden of achieving desegregation. n4 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n4 E.g.  NAACP v. Lansing Board of Education, 429 F.Supp. 583, (W.D. Mich. 1976), aff'd 559 F.2d 1042 (6th Cir. 1977); Arthur v. Nyquist, 473 F.Supp. 830, 839-840 (W.D. NY 1979); Cisneros v. Corpus Christi Independent School District, 467 F.2d 142, 153 (5th Cir. 1972).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Adoption of a voluntary plan for desegregation purposes in Los Angeles will result and has resulted in minority students, the victims of segregation, bearing the burden of desegregation. At the time of trial approximately \b \i0 \ul0 [*19]\b0 \i0 \ul0   18,500 students took part in the PWT program. Only 40 to 50 white children participated. (July 7th Opinion at p. 19 fn. 2; C.T. 17466). This meant that 99.9% of the students in the program were minority. Id. There can be no doubt that it is minority students who bear the burden.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This burden is exacerbated by the long bus rides which result in the implementation of the PWT program. The trial court noted that, under the PWT program, the "average bus ride is 55 minutes each way, which means that thousands of these children are subject to even longer times en route to school." (Id. at 19 (emphasis in original). n5 Under the mandatory portion of the plan, however, bus rides averaged 20 minutes. Valley News 5/20/80, Sec. 1, pg. 10. Given these statistics, it is difficult to imagine how a voluntary plan can be constitutionally countenanced. Perhaps the most significant conclusion reached by the trial court was that the all-voluntary plan was "presented with the full realization by the board that of all the possible approaches to desegregation the voluntary plan would have the least success in desegregating the minority segregated schools." July 7, 1980 Order at 31; C.T. 17478. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n5 The same is true today. We are advised that PWT travel time is as long as 1 hour, 40 minutes and Magnets as long as 1 hour and 55 minutes, with the average PWT route being 50.25 minutes and the Magnet average being 62.92 minutes. The earliest Magnet route begins at 6:05 a.m.; the earliest PWT at 6:15 a.m.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*20]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Not only was the voluntary plan the least successful in achieving desegregation, but the "all-voluntary plan proposed by the respondent board holds no promise of meeting the mandate in the desegregation of minority schools." July 7, 1980 Finding No. 31, at 92-93; C.T. 17338-9 (emphasis supplied). This statement leads to the inevitable conclusion that the board's purpose in seeking to invoke Proposition One and in resisting mandatory assignment and transportation is to impede and obstruct desegregation.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 One final point. The school board extolls the virtues of the voluntary plan and sought to publicize the horrors of mandatory. In the first place, the mandatory provisions of the desegregation plan involved only a small percentage of students. Out of a total of 685 schools in the district only 153 schools were subject to the mandatory portions of the plan. Los Angeles Times, 4/4/81, Part II, p. 1; Valley News, 4/20/81, Section 1, p. 6. Further, out of a total district enrollment of 534, 712 (1980 Racial and Ethnic Survey) only 57,000 students took part in the mandatory plan, both sending and receiving schools. Washington Post, 3/17/81, A14. The actual number of students who were bussed \b \i0 \ul0 [*21]\b0 \i0 \ul0   as that part of this plan were 23,300 (Los Angeles Times, 4/17/81, Valley News 4/20/81, Sec. 1, p. 1) compared to a total of 30, 200 in PWT and magnets. (L.A.U.S.D. Public Information Office).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In the second place, what "horrors" have occurred were within the voluntary part of the plan. The board has, for instance, focussed and brought attention to long bus rides as an argument against "forced bussing." The long rides, however, are the result of the implementation of the voluntary programs and not from the mandatory. n6 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n6 See With All Deliberate Speed: 1954-19   (United States Commission on Civil Rights, November 1981) Transportation of Students, pp. 37-38, and The Effect of Desegregation on Public Education, pp. 39-44.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 B. The Historical Context and Specific Sequence of Events Leading up to the Passage of Proposition One Indicates the Discriminatory Intent of the Amendment
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Under an Arlington Heights analysis, a court reviews the historical background surrounding the amendment's enactment (429 U.S. at 267) and, in particular, the "specific sequence of events leading up (t0) the challenged decision." (Id.) While these are two separate factors, they are mentioned \b \i0 \ul0 [*22]\b0 \i0 \ul0   together because the evidence to be discussed in this section is relevant to both.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 One of the primary purposes of Proposition One was to impede and frustrate desegregation efforts. This purpose was, in fact, noted by the Legislative Analyst in the California Ballot Pamphlet mailed to California voters:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "This proposition would limit the power of California courts to require desegregation." Ballot Pamphlet Pg. 6
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 The main target of this constitutional amendment, however, was one city, i.e. Los Angeles. In the ballot pamphlet, the author of the constitutional amendment commented that "Proposition One does everything the people of California may legally do to stop court-ordered forced busing in Los Angeles and in all other California school districts." Ballot pamphlet, Pg. 9, emphasis in original.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Since one of the purposes of Proposition One was to thwart desegregation efforts in Los Angeles, any analysis of the history and sequence of events surrounding the amendment's enactment must necessarily focus on desegregation efforts in Los Angeles. Any discussion of desegregation in Los Angeles, however, begins and ends with the actions of the school board since they have played a major \b \i0 \ul0 [*23]\b0 \i0 \ul0   role in the history of desegregation in that city. A review of their actions leads to the inescapable conclusion that the board has consistently attempted to "ignore, delay, circumvent, and avoid its responsibility to eliminate segregation." A Generation Deprived, (United States Commission on Civil Rights, 1977 at 87. This conclusion is based on the following:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 (1) they have continued to operate an unconstitutionally segregated school system and have refused to take affirmative steps towards desegregation;
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 (2) when forced, under court order, to develop desegregation plans, the plans were deemed wholly ineffective, and poorly prepared with little or no regard for their desegregative potential;
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 (3) when one of the proposed plans was finally implemented, they sought to instill community opposition to it; and
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 (4) they have used the court system to delay and prevent implementation of desegregation plans.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 To top it all, the Board passed a resolution supporting Proposition 1 and actually lobbied the Governor to sign a bill calling for extraordinary procedures - an early election - for the vote on the Proposition. Exh. 521; 57 R.T. 8515.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 1. The Board Has Refused to Take Action to \b \i0 \ul0 [*24]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Desegregate the Los Angeles School System
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 When this lawsuit was first filed in 1963, the trial court thought the School Board would voluntarily develop a plan for the desegregation of the schools. No such action occurred. (Superior Court July 7, 1980 Opinion at p. 6; C.T. 17453). In its 1970 decision, the trial court concluded that the School Board was guilty of acting in bad faith in that (1) it had failed to take any steps to alleviate the de jure segregation which existed and (2) had, in fact, acted affirmatively to contribute to and perpetuate the segregation. Superior Court May 1970 Findings; C.T. 560-585, 603-606). In 1976, the California Supreme Court also concluded that the "the board had not attempted to alleviate segregation in the district's schools." (A Generation Deprived, supra, at p. 11).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In 1977, hearings were conducted by the United States Commission on Civil Rights regarding desegregation in Los Angeles. The commission concluded that:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "A shifting majority of the numbers of the Los Angeles City Board of Education have violated their oaths of office by refusing for more than 13 years to take any affirmative steps to alleviate the segregation and racial isolation \b \i0 \ul0 [*25]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of students in the Los Angeles Unified School District."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 A Generation Deprived, supra, at 56
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 The Commission also noted that "(i)t is apparent from the history of its actions that the school board will require stimulation from external, independent sources before any meaningful progress is made toward desegregation." Id. at 47.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 2. Plans Proposed by the Board Have Been Constitutionally Defective as well as Ineffective in Ending Segregation
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Commission's belief that the Board would have to be forced to develop a meaningful desegregation plan is borne out by the Board's actions throughout the course of this litigation. It was not until 1977, when the Board was forced to do so by the State Supreme Court, that a desegregation plan was developed and presented to the court. The plan was rejected by the trial court as constitutionally infirm. (Superior Court Order of July 5, 1977; C.T. 2267).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The second Board plan was also found to be insufficient, but was reluctantly allowed to be implemented in 1978 in order to start desegregation efforts. (Superior Court Order of Feb. 7, 1978; C.T. 6934).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In 1979, the Board presented an all-voluntary plan for approval by the court.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 On July 7, 1980, the \b \i0 \ul0 [*26]\b0 \i0 \ul0   trial court rendered its opinion of this plan. It noted that:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "the respondent board does not have a course of action which is designed to make meaningful progress in the elimination of harms arising out of minority segregated schools, and... does not appear to have resolved itself to achieve any such plan in the near future."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 (July 7 Opin. at p. 3; C.T. 17450)
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 As to the merits of the plan itself, the court rejected the plan because:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "1. It is not designed to desegregate any of the minority schools of the Los Angeles Unified School District.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 2. It treats minority children with less concern than other children in the district.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 3. It relies entirely upon the voluntary compliance of the mandate by the children and their parents, which reliance is neither reasonable nor realistic.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 4. Its provisions, viewed in light of the board's activities, do not demonstrate the board's commitment, even if given more time, to take additional steps to produce meaningful progress in the desegregation of the district's minority schools and the alleviation of the harms arising from segregation.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 ( Id. at 5, C.T. 17452)
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The trial court commented on the plan (Plan II)  \b \i0 \ul0 [*27]\b0 \i0 \ul0   that had been in operation since the 1978-79 school year: "The manner in which the plan was executed carried the seeds of failure to achieve its limited goals." (Trial Court Opinion and Findings, July 7, 1980, p. 3; C.T. 17450). As to the Board's all-voluntary plan, the court found that it was "hastily conceived," "not thoroughly planned," and was "presented with the full realization by the board that of all the possible approaches to desegregation the voluntary plan would have the least success in desegregating the minority segregated schools." Id. at 31, C.T. 17478.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 3. The Board Has Sought to Instill Community Opposition to Desegregation.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Perhaps the most destructive action taken by the board, however, is its public opposition to desegregation efforts. Certain Board members have purposefully sought to instill community opposition to desegregation rather than community support. The Civil Rights Commission believes that official support is necessary in order to achieve desegregation:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "The peaceful implementation of desegregation is not by chance. One of the most important conclusions of this report is that the support of school officials and other local leaders strongly \b \i0 \ul0 [*28]\b0 \i0 \ul0   influences the outcome of desegregation. The public generally follows the lead of officials who are responsible for school desegregation...." at 223
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The Commission found that "The leadership factor is the most crucial component in the peaceful implementation of desegregation. In communities where leaders either voice opposition to desegregation or refuse to support the effort publicly, the result is often chaotic, with confusion, anxiety, turmoil and disruption prevailing." at 224. This is precisely the situation that occurred in Los Angeles.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In 1976, the Commission expressed strong concern that officials in Los Angeles, including school board members, were making public statements which were designed to "reinforce community fears about the negative potential of school desegregation." A Generation Deprived, supra, at 83.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 When the Commission conducted its hearings in 1977, it found a wide range of community, religious, labor, business, and other organization support for integration. Id. at 100-152. Organizations such as ourselves still strongly support desegregation efforts. Rather than drawing upon this support, however, the Board has sought to undermine this support by instilling \b \i0 \ul0 [*29]\b0 \i0 \ul0   fear in the Los Angeles community about desegregation. A present example of this is found in the Board's actions after the trial court rendered its May 19, 1980 opinion. One Board member, before even reading the opinion, made the following statement which was published in a number of Los Angeles newspapers:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "If I was a white parent I'd be looking for a private school or looking for a new home outside the Los Angeles Unified School District."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Los Angeles Herald Examiner, 5-20-80, A7.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 Another Board member commented that:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "(Judge Egley's order, if allowed to stand) will bring about the devastation of the public school system."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Id.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 As reported in one newspaper, a third member "referred to the explosion Sunday of Mt. St. Helens in the State of Washington and said a "volcano of similar proportions has erupted from the Egly courtroom." Valley News 5-20-80, \'a7 1, p. 4.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The trial court, after rendering its July 7, 1980 opinion, had ordered meetings to be held to explain the new plan, to seek community input into the plan, and to help alleviate concerns that parents might have about the plan. The board's response, however, was to use these meetings to publicly oppose the plan,  \b \i0 \ul0 [*30]\b0 \i0 \ul0   to tell parents that the plan would not work, and to create uncertainty in the minds of the parents. Meetings were held at elementary schools in the district. "At each meeting a letter was read in which the Board of Education disavowed responsibility for the desegregation plan. Board members, including the President of the Board, appeared at several meetings in the San Fernando Valley to tell parents the board opposed the busing order." Los Angeles Times, 8-13-80, Part I, p. 3. One letter from concerned parents dramatically portrays the intent of the board to instill opposition to desegregation:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "You ask if you will still be in junior chorus and we have to tell you we have been told by the school board that most of the extras you enjoyed are being eliminated to pay for the integration plan."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Los Angeles Herald Examiner, A19, 9-12-80.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 4. The Board Has Used the Court System to Obstruct Desegregation Efforts
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 One of the Board's tactics in achieving its goal of preventing the desegregation of the Los Angeles School System has been to appeal virtually every court order. The most dramatic demonstration of this concerns the board's actions in regard to Plan II which was implemented \b \i0 \ul0 [*31]\b0 \i0 \ul0   in 1978. That plan, although constitutionally infirm, was accepted in order to make some movement towards desegregation of the Los Angeles School system. But the Board joined with Bustop, an intervening organization from San Fernando Valley, and asked the State Supreme Court to continue a stay of its very own plan. Crawford v. Court of Appeal, L.A. Civil No. 31018, Memorandum of Board of Education dated September 5, 1978, p. 2. In 1979, it again attempted to halt the continuation of its own plan and recommended that another, this time an allvoluntary plan, be accepted. While this plan was before the trial court, Proposition One passed.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 After the passage of the constitutional amendment, the Board's immediate response was to invoke the provisions of Proposition One. With the passage of the constitutional amendment, the board believed that it would finally accomplish its purpose of bringing desegregation efforts to a halt in Los Angeles. The trial court ruled, however, that since the Board had been found guilty of intentional discrimination in the operation of its segregated school system, Proposition One was not applicable. May 19, 1980 Minute Order, C.T. 16850.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The result of the \b \i0 \ul0 [*32]\b0 \i0 \ul0   trial court's ruling was more appeals, culminating in the appeal presently before this Court. On July 7, 1980, the trial court, because of the refusal of the board to develop a workable desegregation plan, was forced to develop a plan itself. July 7, 1980 Opinion; C.T. 17452. The Board refused to cooperate with the court in developing a workable desegregation plan for the coming school year: "While the appeals were pending the judge and his aides, with virtually no help from the board, worked on implementation of his ruling." Washington Post, 9-12-80, Pt. A-20. All of the Board's efforts were in the direction of preventing, through the court system, the implementation of the plan, and specifically, preventing mandatory pupil assignment and transportation, despite the fact that it knew that mandatory plans were the only effective way of desegregating the minority segregated schools. Rather than taking the time to reassure students and parents and apprising them of what they could expect at the commencement of the new school year, it focussed all its efforts on blocking the implementation of the plan. As a result, the Los Angeles school system remains in the same condition it was in \b \i0 \ul0 [*33]\b0 \i0 \ul0   1963, with no desegregation.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 C. The Procedural and Substantive Departures From Longstanding California Institutional Structures In This Case Clearly Manifest A Discriminatory Purpose
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In Arlington Heights, the Court recognized that "Departures from the normal procedural sequence also might afford evidence that improper purposes are playing a role. Substantive departures too may be relevant, particularly if the factors usually considered important by the decisionmaker strongly favor a decision contrary to the one reached." 429 U.S. at 267.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Perhaps the most reprehensible feature of Proposition One is that it was designed to apply not only to future desegregation actions, but also was specifically calculated to directly interfere with this case, n7 a case in which rights had already been secured by a final judgment that had been sustained by the California Supreme Court ( Crawford v. Board of Education, 17 Cal.3d 280 (1976)). 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n7 "Except as may be precluded by the Constitution of the United States, every existing judgment, decree, writ, or other order of a court of this state, whenever rendered, which includes provisions regarding pupil assignment or pupil transportation, or which requires a plan including such provisions shall, upon application to a court having jurisdiction by any interested person, be modified to conform to the provisions of this subdivision as amended, as applied to the facts which exist at the time of such modification." (emphasis added)
\par \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb0 \fi0 That this was directed specifically at the 1970 judgment in Crawford is clear beyond peradventure of doubt.
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*34]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This extraordinary interference with the orderly enforcement of rights secured by a final judgment n8 plainly departs from longstanding and fundamental California institutional safeguards and structures. The willingness to depart from these structures itself is compelling evidence of discriminatory purpose. Specifically, this aspect of Proposition One runs roughshod over (1) the understanding that it is a special function of the judiciary in California to protect the rights of minorities against the excesses of the majority together with California's strong policy of affording access to the courts to assure that the rights of the minority shall not be abused; and (2) the strong California policy that rights secured in litigation shall not be taken away by legislation retroactively applied. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n8 We note this is not a case where the issue is whether changes in law should apply to trial court judgments not yet finalized in the appellate process. Even there, serious constitutional questions are implicated. See, e.g., Mirabel v. General Motors Acceptance Corp., 537 F.2d 871, 875 n. 3 (7th Cir. 1976).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 1. The Special Function of the California Judiciary in Protecting \b \i0 \ul0 [*35]\b0 \i0 \ul0   Minorities and the Related Policy of Affording Access to the Courts Have Been Uniquely Violated in This Case
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 If there is any aspect of the constitutional system that unites commentators and the fifty states, it is that a vital function of the courts is to protect minorities against the exdesses of the majority. This court put it in Chambers v. Florida, 309 U.S. 227, 241 (1940), "Under our Constitutional system, courts stand against any winds that blow as houses of refuge for those who might suffer because they are helpless, weak, outnumbered, or because they are nonconforming victims of prejudice and public excitement." California is in accord. See, e.g., Committee to Defend Reproductive Rights v. Meyers, 29 Cal.3d 252, 281 (1981) (poor afforded special protection beyond federal constitutional requirements because they share "many characteristics of other 'insular minorities who may not be adequately protected from discriminatory treatment by the general safeguards of the legislative process."); Accord, Sail'er Inn. v. Kirby, 5 Cal.3d 1, 19 (1971) (women afforded special constitutional protection beyond federal constitutional standards because \b \i0 \ul0 [*36]\b0 \i0 \ul0   of "second class citizenship... Women, like Negroes, aliens, and the poor have historically labored under severe legal and social disabilities."); Purdy and Fitzpatrick v. California, 71 Cal.2d 566, 578-79 (1969) (anticipating Graham v. Richardson, 403 U.S. 365 (1971) aliens entitled to strict standard of review because of risk of prejudice "a special mandate compels us to guard the interests of aliens.")
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 What is unusual about this case is not that a majority would try to change policy (protecting minorities) in the future; n9 what is striking is that a state majority would in unprecedented fashion actually seek to interfere with a court's judgment in Los Angeles. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n9 Even as to that issue, we believe a rational basis test would be patently insufficient. This Court, to be sure, in Dayton II, 443 U.S. at 531, n. 5, observed that rescission of prior resolutions supporting desegregation would be unconstitutional only if the resolutions were required in the first place by the Fourteenth Amendment. We make two observations. First, the question of whether states may rescind protections for minorities is not the same as whether some degree of heightened scrutiny should be afforded when that is done. Given the special concern of the Thirteenth and Fourteenth Amendments for protecting minorities, actions taken to deprive them of benefits important to eliminate badges of servitude deserve a measure of judicial concern greater than that afforded to Oklahoma opticians. See, Williamson v. Lee Optical, 348 U.S. 483, 488 (1955). Second, recission of benefits to minorities when done with an improper purpose is unconstitutional.  Personnel Administrator v. Feeney, 442 U.S. 256, 272 (1979).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb0 \fi0  \b \i0 \ul0 [*37]\b0 \i0 \ul0  
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The distortion of California's policy of judicial protection for minorities rights is best exposed in colloboration with the violation of its equally strong policy of access to the courts. In Payne v. Superior Court, 17 Cal.3d 908, 911 (1976), the California Supreme Court observed that "In a variety of contexts, the right of access to the courts has been reaffirmed and strengthened throughout our 100-year history. Moreover, it affirmed that the right "'includes access to all courts... without regard to the type of petition or relief sought'".  Id. 914 (emphasis added). In substance, what Proposition One says to petitioners is this: "You have won rights to school assignments and desegregated education in the one institution specially designed to protect your rights. We take that away. Now, go to a political institution dominated by a majority and forego any access to the courts to enforce the rights you have won." This is unprecedented. Its departure from settled practice is so extreme as to negate professed desires to save gas, preserve the environment or imagined worries about school bus safety. n10 The "departure" feature of Arlington Heights has been satisfied.  \b \i0 \ul0 [*38]\b0 \i0 \ul0   A discriminatory purpose is present. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n10 These purposes are obvious makeweights unless somehow school bus safety or the environment is better protected by buses that ride pursuant to a "voluntary" program. Other state purposes such as preserving harmony and tranquility in the state simply cater to race prejudice. Cf.  Edwards v. South Carolina, 372 U.S. 229 (1963) (answer to hostile audience problem is to quiet the audience in the absence of inability to control it).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 2. Depriving the Petitioners of Rights Vested in Litigation Itself Violates California Policy and Manifests Discriminatory Purpose
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Proposition One conclusively carves out an exception to California's policy that final judgments are final, that rights won in litigation have vested. That exception applies to minority students seeking to secure their state guaranteed right to desegregate education and to them only.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 As far back as 1857, the California Supreme Court declared that legislation impairing vested rights is "repugnant to the plainest principles of morality and justice, and is violative of the spirit and letter of our Constitution..." Billings v. Hall, 7 Cal. 1, 11-12 (1957). Since \b \i0 \ul0 [*39]\b0 \i0 \ul0   then it has been uniformly recognized that the legislature is without power to impair or destroy the obligations of contractual or vested rights, and any statute which affects a vested right cannot be given retrospective operation.  Pardee Construction Co. v. Californis Coastal Commission, 95 Cal.App.3d 471, 479 (1979). n11 See also Miller v. McKenna, 23 Cal.2d 774 (1974). 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n11 No different standard applies when the attempted divestiture takes place via the amendment process. See Farat v. Kingsburg, 98 Cal.App. 284, 291 (1929).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Similarly, there is no doubt that final judgments are vested rights in California. See, e.g., Kendall v. Kendall, 122 Cal.App. 397 (1932); Barrett v. Superior Court, 104 Cal.App. 657 (1930; 13 Cal.Jur.3d \'a7 275 at 515 (1974) ("Like a common-law cause of action, a judgment is such a vested right of of property that the legislature cannot, by a retroactive law either destroy or diminish its value in any respect.")
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The treatment by the court below of the vested rights argument was cryptic and evasive. First, without any explanation, it announced that the only vested right in the case was the \b \i0 \ul0 [*40]\b0 \i0 \ul0   right to be free of intentionally segregative action.  113 Cal.App.3d at 655. But that simply ignored the existence of the 1976 decision of the California Supreme Court in this case which, if it did nothing else, plainly reaffirmed the continuing right of minority students to be free of segregation where reasonable and feasible steps could be taken to cure the condition. Here, as described in Arlington Heights, the factors usually considered important in California n12 were ignored. 
\par \pard 
\par \fs16 \pard \ql \li600\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 n12 These factors, of course, have independent federal constitutional significance. See generally Hochman, The Supreme Court and the Constitutionality of Retroactive Legislation, 73 Harv.L.Rev. 692 (1960).
\par \fs20 \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Second, the court below observed that "all" the amendment did was to "remove from the Courts the remedy of pupil school assignments and pupil transportation as one among scores of remedies available for use by a court to end racial isolation." Id. at 655-656. This was ingenuous. As we have previously discussed, the supporters well knew what they were doing in designing the amendment. A court cannot end segregation if it cannot compel the assignment of students. That has \b \i0 \ul0 [*41]\b0 \i0 \ul0   been this Court's experience in numerous cases in the South and the North. California has long recognized that the removal of a remedy vital to the protection of a vested right is the same as removing the right itself: "Of course, the removal of all, or substantially all, of an individual's remedies for enforcing a right would have the same practical effect as destroying the right itself. 'Remedies are the life of rights.'" Flournoy v. California, 230 Cal.App.2d 520 (1964).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The court's brief and revealing discussion of the vested rights issue highlights the unusual steps taken in this case. A state senator from Los Angeles and a school board reacting to constitutents fueled by the same fears and stereotypes that have motivated citizens to resist desegregation in Dayton, Columbus, and elsewhere transformed those fears into law. The racial fears of Los Angeles are entitled to no more respect than those with similar fears in the South and the North. The evidence overwhelmingly points to the conclusion that segregative intent is present here and that the special role of the courts in protecting minority children must not be abandoned.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 From the above, it is clearly seen \b \i0 \ul0 [*42]\b0 \i0 \ul0   that the criteria of Arlington Heights have been met and that Proposition One should not be allowed to stand. If the Court is not satisfied, however, that this discussion has demonstrated that fact, the case should be remanded for the evidentiary hearing contemplated by Arlington Heights. We discuss this in the following section.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 III
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 A REMAND OF THIS CASE IS APPROPRIATE IN ORDER THAT FINDINGS OF FACT BE MADE ON THE ISSUE OF WHETHER THERE WAS AN UNDERLYING DISCRIMINATORY PURPOSE BEHIND THE ENACTMENT OF PROPOSITION ONE
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In its May 19, 1980 order, the trial court relied on its 1970 ruling as affirmed by the California Supreme Court in 1976 that the Los Angeles School Board had been guilty of de jure segregation in violation of the Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution. As a result, the trial court did not reach the issue of the constitutionality of Proposition One. Evidence on the issue of intent to discriminate had been produced by the petitioners below, although no rebuttal evidence was introduced by the School Board. The trial court, since it did not reach the issue, did not make any relevant findings of fact.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Nor did the Court below examine the evidence on \b \i0 \ul0 [*43]\b0 \i0 \ul0   the issue of intent. Instead, it refused to look past the purposes recited in the constitutional amendment itself in clear violation of the requirements of this Court's opinion in Arlington Heights, supra (113 Cal.App.3d 633 at 654-655.) The Court of Appeal then, without a single reference to the evidence, dismissed as "pure speculation" the possibility that intent to effect racial segregation was a motivating factor in Proposition One's passage. But in the next sentence the Court itself, again without reference to any evidence in the trial court, speculated as to the possible permissible purposes behind Proposition One. Crawford II, supra, at 655.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This Court's opinion in Arlington Heights recognized that "(d)etermining whether invidious discriminatory purpose was a motivating factor demands a sensitive inquiry into such circumstantial and direct evidence of intent as may be available." Arlington Heights, supra, 429 U.S. at 266. No such inquiry was made in this case.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 This Court and its varying members have acknowledged that the inquiry into the factual evidence of unconstitutional purpose should be made in the first instance by the trial court, subject \b \i0 \ul0 [*44]\b0 \i0 \ul0   to review by appellate courts.  Dayton II, 433 U.S. at 419. "The District Court, in the first instance, subject to review by the Court of Appeals, must make new findings and conclusions as to violations in light of this opinion, Washington v. Davis, and Arlington Heights..." Id. (citations omitted). Realizing the difficulty of the task, this Court remanded the case to the trier of fact to make the complex factual determinations in the first instance." Id. See also the concurring opinion by Brennan, J., Id. at 421, 422 (supporting the remand to the District Court); Keyes v. School District No. 1 (1972) 413 U.S. 189, 205 (case remanded to district court for resolution of factual matters).
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The opinion in Columbus also provides support for a remand. The majority opinion acknowledged that the role of the trier of fact is to make findings which will not be disturbed by the Court of Appeals or by this Court unless the findings are clearly erroneous.  443 U.S. at 454-55. Justices Stewart and Burger agreed. Finally, Justice Rehnquist stated:
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 "I do not suggest that the inquiry required by Dayton I and Keyes is a simple one, and reviewing \b \i0 \ul0 [*45]\b0 \i0 \ul0   courts must defer to the findings of District Court judges. But appellate courts also must ensure that these judges are asing themselves the right questions: it is clear in the instant case that critical questions regarding causality and purpose were not asked at all."
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Rehnquist, J., dissenting.  Id. at 524.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 In the instant case, no factual findings were ever made regarding the issue of intent to discriminate. The Court of Appeal did not ask any questions. This case indicates, therefore, a remand for factual findings. It is the belief of amici that a remand will result in a finding of discriminatory intent. The evidence supporting such a finding is, in fact, overwhelming, as demonstrated by the previous discussion in this brief.
\par \pard 
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 CONCLUSION
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 The judgment below should be reversed or, in the alternative, the case remanded for the preparation of findings of fact on the issue of discriminatory intent and/or for the holding of a hearing thereon.
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 Respectfully submitted,
\par \pard \ql \li0\ri0 \sb120 \fi360 ALICE MONTGOMERY, AMY RODNEY, STEVEN SHIFFRIN, Attorneys for Amici Curiae, African American Education, Commission, et al.
\par \pard 
